    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 11th with a clear priority on speed-adjacent upside, anchored by **Trea Turner** (72.23), our highest-projected asset. **Trea Turner** benefits immensely from a favorable matchup against Pfaadt, where a slow delivery increases his stolen base equity, further boosted by the lead-off spot. **Yordan Alvarez** (68.04) and **Kyle Schwarber** (65.95) provide the necessary high-floor production to supplement our counting stats, with **Kyle Schwarber** thriving in his high-run-expectancy role batting second. Despite the stiff challenge of facing Luis Castillo, **Yordan Alvarez** remains a locked-in start due to his elite xwOBA, proving that even against ace-caliber talent, his raw power profile is indispensable for our Roto categories.\n\nWe are navigating several \"Lineup Pending\" designations, requiring strict adherence to our efficiency thresholds. **Christian Yelich** (40.96) barely clears our roster floor; his projection suffered significantly due to a poor platoon matchup against the 2.70 xERA of Foster Griffin. The most difficult personnel decision fell at the final bench spot, where **Josh Smith** (42.06) narrowly missed the cut. While **Josh Smith** offered strong dynamic platoon upside, he was edged out by the superior park-adjusted score of **Jerar Encarnacion** (52.88). **Jerar Encarnacion** benefits from a massive park factor boost (+16%) that outweighs **Josh Smith**'s situational utility. Conversely, **Victor Scott II** (35.34) and **Carson Benge** (39.27) were relegated to the bench primarily because of their sub-40 scores, with **Victor Scott II** particularly suppressed by a tough matchup against Suarez and poor projected batting order placement. Owners should monitor the status of **Hyeseong Kim** and **Caleb Durbin**, as any movement out of their projected spots could invite volatility into today's final outcomes.",
